article.headline: Hawaii 70, Idaho 66
article.story: MOSCOW, Idaho (AP) -- Julian Sensley and Deonte Tatum scored 19 and 17 points, respectively, and Hawaii overcame a 10-point halftime deficit to defeat Idaho 70-66 Wednesday night in a Western Athletic Conference game. The Rainbow Warriors (15-9, 8-5 WAC) came out firing to start the second half, hitting 14 of 17 shots, including all five of their 3-point tries. Hawaii wound up converting 15 of 21 second-half shots (71.4 percent) after an 11-for-27 (40.7 percent) showing in the first half. Sensley made good on 7 of 11 shots from the field and 5 of 7 from 3-point range, and Tatum went 7-for-10 from the floor. Hawaii used a 19-6 run to erase a 43-37 deficit and surge ahead 56-49 with 10:45 remaining. The Warriors never trailed again, although Idaho (4-21, 1-12) pulled within 64-62 following an 8-0 run that was capped by a Brett Ledbetter steal and layup with 5:28 to play. Neither team scored again until Sensley buried a 3-pointer with 2:55 to go, and after four straight Idaho points, Hawaii was clinging to a 67-66 advantage when Ahmet Gueye stepped to the line for a pair of free throws with 13.9 seconds remaining. Gueye hit both attempts, and Ledbetter missed a 3-pointer at the other end with five seconds remaining. Hawaii's Matt Lojeski then hit one of two free throw attempts with 1.4 seconds left. Gueye added 15 points and eight rebounds for Hawaii, which was 1-7 on the road coming into the game. Idaho was led by junior guard Keoni Watson's 22 points.
